<body>

    <h1>Neuroembryology Learning Module</h1>

    <div class="section">
        <h2>Learning Objectives</h2>
        <ul>
            <li>Understand formation of neural plate, tube, and crest cells</li>
            <li>Identify brain vesicle development</li>
            <li>Recognize clinical correlations of neural tube defects</li>
        </ul>
    </div>

    <div class="section">
        <h2>Formation of Neural Plate, Neural Tube, and Neural Crest Cells</h2>
        <p>The CNS appears at the beginning of the third week as a slipper-shaped plate of thickened ectoderm known as the <strong>neural plate</strong>. The neural plate lies cranial to the primitive node and extends to the buccopharyngeal membrane. The lateral margins elevate and become the <strong>neural folds</strong>, which give rise to <strong>neural crest cells</strong>. Fusion of the neural folds forms the <strong>neural tube</strong>.</p>
        <ul>
            <li>Cranial neuropore closes ~day 25</li>
            <li>Caudal neuropore closes ~day 28</li>
        </ul>
        <h3>Clinical Correlations</h3>
        <ul>
            <li><strong>Anencephaly:</strong> No neural development above brainstem</li>
            <li><strong>Encephalocele:</strong> Skull defect allows brain protrusion</li>
            <li><strong>Rachischisis:</strong> Posterior neuropore fails to close</li>
            <li><strong>Craniorachischisis:</strong> Entire brain and spinal cord exposed</li>
        </ul>
    </div>

    <div class="section">
        <h2>Neural Tube Defects</h2>
        <ul>
            <li><strong>Occulta:</strong> Malformed vertebrae</li>
            <li><strong>Meningocele:</strong> Membranes protrude through vertebral defect</li>
            <li><strong>Meningomyelocele:</strong> Neural tissue exposed through spinal opening</li>
        </ul>
    </div>

    <div class="section">
        <h2>Formation of Brain Vesicles and Ventricles</h2>
        <p>Cephalic end of neural tube dilates, forming the 3 primary brain vesicles: <strong>prosencephalon</strong> (forebrain), <strong>mesencephalon</strong> (midbrain), <strong>rhombencephalon</strong> (hindbrain).</p>
        <p>Secondary vesicles:</p>
        <ul>
            <li>Telencephalon, Diencephalon (from prosencephalon)</li>
            <li>Mesencephalon remains</li>
            <li>Metencephalon, Myelencephalon (from rhombencephalon)</li>
        </ul>
        <p>The ventricular system develops from the hollow neural tube cavity, later filled with cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) secreted by the choroid plexus.</p>
    </div>

